msgid "Text frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:23
# 1d6ef34b7ef24b1d8355a8784a130034
msgid "Text \"Boxes\" allow you to distribute the text amongst rectangular areas within a single text object. An arbitrary number of freely positionable and re-sizable text frames are allowed per text object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:27
# 40da6daf84f64ecca0f5439eaa31b6ab
msgid "Text flows continuously from the lowest-numbered frame to the highest-numbered frame with text inside each frame word-wrapped. Text flows between frames when a lower-numbered frame can't fit any more text. If the last frame is reached, text overflows out of it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:32
# 0838766e3a4d4fc8899370222169bfaa
msgid "Text frames are very similar to the concept of *frames* from a desktop publishing application, like Scribus. You use frames to control the placement and flow of text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:35
# 6fed635d0ba04a3bbd20e884c830d141
msgid "Frames are controlled in the *Text Boxes* panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:39
# 8eb95d4b78da4e1bbb732d067b88943a
msgid "Frame size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:41
# 48b34d6e284045508a7f015f32e3d8ec
msgid "By default the first frame for a new text object, and any additional frames, has a size of **zero** for both *Width* and *Height*, which means the frame is initially not visible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:45
# 63df4e88eab24d05ba02b5658771675d
msgid "Frames with a width of **0.0** are ignored completely during text flow (no wordwrap happens), and frames with a height of **0.0** flow forever (no flowing to the next text frame)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:49
# 9d35383169824c919bc3dc4a0d37134f
msgid "In order for the frame to become visible, the frame's *Width* must be greater than **0.0**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:55
# 12ec97dde2394fbbbf40aa5be998b929
msgid "Technically the height is never actually **0.0** because the font itself always contributes height."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:61
# a8c74c3c247b4f3fa946131faf981a97
msgid "Frame width."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:64
# 6d29acfbc9874244af870119cdad9caf
msgid "(*Frame width*) is a text object with a width of ``5.0``. And because the frame width is greater than ``0.0`` it is now visible and is drawn in the active theme color as a dashed rectangle. The text has overflowed because the text has reached the end of the last frame, the default frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:71
# 5f8ed26bf33540a7a193e4890bf509e0
msgid "Adding/Deleting a Frame"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:73
# 077fa4ebd0af4109bf64a77e214df134
msgid "To add a frame click the *Add Textbox* button on the *Text Boxes* panel. A new frame is inserted just after (in text flow order) the current one, with its attributes (position and size). Be sure to modify the offset for the new frame in the *X* and/or *Y* fields. Just an *X* modification will create a new column."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:78
# aef861668e3048dda2e8c8d5f0d30f44
msgid "To delete the current frame, click the :kbd:`Delete` button. Any text in higher frames will be re-flowed downward into lower frames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:83
# 33f4d0d721444f07a6c9d460640018e7
msgid "Example: Text Flow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:88
# 7c922b6bf96542abbd03ebc91d1f58fb
msgid "wrapping"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:91
# 86433bb9ac7f478e901458c239098c06
msgid "With two or more frames you can organize text to a finer degree. For example, create a text object and enter ``Blender is super duper``. This text object has a frame; it just isn't visible because its *Width* is **0.0**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:97
# da0eb1265a5b4a02b9e891218e41267b
msgid "Set the width to **5.0**. The frame is now visible and text is wrapping according to the new width, as shown in (*Text 2*). Notice that the text has overflowed out of the frame. This is because the text has reached the end of the last frame, which just happens to be the default/initial frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:107
# fb51b694aab14e289f3e01a2856e7416
msgid "text flowing from box 1 to box 2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:110
# 9458c8293b224c2caf6e04f322a88ec2
msgid "When we add another frame and set its width and height, the text will flow into the new frame."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:114
# a3eb8ff6df2b46019f8aa9bf9c83529e
msgid "Example: Multiple columns"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:119
# 2ac6153776d845c0a41a19e3a2a97bb5
msgid "Text 5."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:122
# bc4ce455c4554f898ab30c8d74f85474
msgid "To create two columns of text just create a text object and adjust the initial frame's *Width* and *Height* to your requirements, then insert a new frame. The new frame will have the same size as the initial frame. Set the *X* position to something greater or less than the width of the initial frame; see (*Text 5*)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:129
# 589e2476ccfc4ecb8febbcca3d7e32d8
msgid "Assigning Materials"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:138
# 5cd46281989343ce9825e6312d433269
msgid "Each character can have a different *Material index* in order to have different materials on different characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:141
# a0051eaa59f646ee860629a24a7a6afc
msgid "You can assign indices either as you type, or after by selecting blocks of text and clicking on the *Assign* button in the Materials panel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:148
# 0e3d78ff52e64657acb23c7d48925578
msgid "Red Green Blue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../manual/modeling/texts/editing.rst:151
# 1152fa553af748efb99e6f5287f1c075
msgid "For example, to create (*Red Green Blue*) you would need to create three separate materials and three separate material indices. Each word would be assigned a *Material index* by selecting the characters for each word and clicking the *Assign* button. (*Red Green Blue*) is still one single *Text* object."
msgstr ""

